    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The p-value of 0.04 is a statistical significance level, which is a measure of how likely it is that the observed results are due to chance. In this case, a p-value of 0.04 means that if the new blood pressure med had no effect on blood pressure, there's only a 4% chance that we'd see the observed results (or more extreme) by chance alone. It's like a coin toss - if you flip a coin 10,000 times, you'd expect to get a result like this about 4 times by chance. \n\nHowever, it's essential to consider the context of the trial, such as sample size, study duration, and the specific results. A p-value of 0.04 doesn't necessarily mean the treatment is effective, but it does suggest that the results are statistically significant. \n\nIn the world of clinical trials, a p-value is often compared to a predetermined significance level, typically set at 0.05. If the p-value falls below this threshold, the researchers can conclude that the observed results are statistically significant. Think of it like a threshold for \"good enough\" - if the p-value is below 0.05, the treatment is considered to have",
